    It will generally comprise a function of some kind and a marshaller
    used to call it. It is the responsibility of the marshaller to
    convert the arguments for the invocation from [GValues]:class:`Value` into
    a suitable form, perform the callback on the converted arguments,
    and transform the return value back into a :class:`Value`.

    In the case of C programs, a closure usually just holds a pointer
    to a function and maybe a data argument, and the marshaller
    converts between :class:`Value` and native C types. The :class:`GObject.Object`
    library provides the :class:`CClosure` type for this purpose. Bindings for
    other languages need marshallers which convert between [GValues]:class:`Value`
    and suitable representations in the runtime of the language in
    order to use functions written in that language as callbacks. Use
    :meth:`Closure.set_marshal` to set the marshaller on such a custom
    closure implementation.

    Within :class:`GObject.Object`, closures play an important role in the
    implementation of signals. When a signal is registered, the
    ``c_marshaller`` argument to :func:`signal_new` specifies the default C
    marshaller for any closure which is connected to this
    signal. :class:`GObject.Object` provides a number of C marshallers for this
    purpose, see the ``g_cclosure_marshal_*()`` functions. Additional C
    marshallers can be generated with the [glib-genmarshal][glib-genmarshal]
    utility.  Closures can be explicitly connected to signals with
    :func:`signal_connect_closure`, but it usually more convenient to let
    :class:`GObject.Object` create a closure automatically by using one of the
    ``g_signal_connect_*()`` functions which take a callback function/user
    data pair.

